## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | .NET 8 behavior | Replacement |
|-----|-----------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (no abort = no exception) | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit
                // naturally on the next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — cooperative, not forcible

        // Wait for the thread to finish (replaces Sleep + Abort)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept & respect the token.** If it blocks (e.g., on a queue), the old `Abort` would force-interrupt it. Cooperative cancellation won't — the method must check the token:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely, relied on Abort to escape
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever if queue is empty
}

// After (.NET 8) — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If `GetNextItem` does synchronous I/O or calls code you can't modify, cancellation will stall until that call returns naturally. That's the fundamental trade-off — move to async I/O or accept the delay.

**2. `Thread.Sleep` → `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne`.** If any code in the chain calls `Thread.Sleep`, it won't respond to cancellation. Replace:

```csharp
// Won't respond to cancellation:
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// Will wake immediately on cancel:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

**3. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers and callbacks. The class now implements `IDisposable` for this reason.

**4. `Join` replaces `Sleep` + `Abort`.** The original code slept 2 seconds then force-killed. `Join(timeout)` is cleaner — it blocks until the thread exits *or* the timeout elapses. After `Join`, if the thread is still alive, you have no force-kill option in .NET 8; you must ensure the code cooperates.
